<Rewrite PAsource="" >A SENIOR executive in the </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >oil </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >industry who was dismissed when he returned to work after being treated for </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >cancer </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >has been awarded £82,000 by an employment </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >tribunal.</Verbatim>


<Verbatim PAsource="" >The tribunal</Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >, sitting in Aberdeen, </New>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >ruled yesterday that </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Tom McLauchlan, 52, </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >had been unfairly discriminated against because </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >his employers </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >did not take </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >account </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >of the effects of his </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >illness </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >when assessing his </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >performance </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >at work.</Rewrite>


<Rewrite PAsource="" >He was awarded </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >£79,708 for disability discrimination and £2,310 for unfair dismissal </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >- the second-</Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >biggest award </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >for such a case in Britain.</Rewrite>


<Verbatim PAsource="" >Mr McLauchlan, a loss prevention manager, </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >was dismissed from his </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >£60,000</Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >-a-year job </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >in July, 1998, by </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >his employers, </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Stolt Comex Seaway Ltd.</Verbatim>

